{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, according to Google Scholar, 9 the AIHEd review by Zawacki-Richter et al. (2019) has been cited 1256 times since it was published, with the article accessed over 215,000 times and appearing six times in written news stories, 10 indicating a wide-ranging public interest in AIHEd.",
    "Prior AIHEd tertiary syntheses have so far also taken place within secondary research (e.g., systematic reviews), rather than as standalone reviews of reviews such as this one.",
    "Saghiri et al. (2022), for example, included an analysis of four systematic reviews in their scoping review of AI applications in dental education, de Oliveira et al. (2021) included eight reviews in their systematic review of educational data mining for recommender systems, and Sapci and Sapci (2020) included five reviews in their systematic review of medical education.",
    "However, by synthesising both primary and secondary studies within the one review, there is a risk of study duplication, and authors need to be particularly careful to ensure that a primary study identified for inclusion is not also included in one of the secondary studies, to ensure that the results presented are accurate, and the review conducted to a high quality.",
    "Literature reviews (or narrative reviews) are the most commonly known form of secondary research; however, a range of evidence synthesis methods have increasingly emerged, particularly from the field of health care."
  ]
}